in Cic. Dav. quotes from Quint. xii 2 ‘qui plus in hoe studii dederunt.’ The rarer phrase operam inpendimus (OPERJ. INPFLDIMUS) differs by little more than one letter from operam dedimus, which would tend to come in by error, but operam may have come in as a gloss to dedimus. Mur. suggested the omission of operam and Lamb. ejected the word.

scholas, ‘dissertations,' cf. 47, 113. Dav. compares Quint. iii 1 ⁶ pomeridianis scholis'3 T.D. iii 34, 81; Fin. ii 1, 1; Diog. L. x πός Plut. περὶ τοῦ ἀκούειν, init. τὴν γενομένην μοι σχολὴν περὶ τοῦ ἀκούειν ἀπέσταλκά σοι γράψας. Ktih. notes that Plutarch was the first to use the word in this sense. An Eng. scholar in Mo„ be- lieved by Mo. to be Bentley, distinguishes between scholae in this sense and dis- putationes strictly so called, such as the Academics, de Diu.. Fin., and N.D. In disputationes philosophers in turn set forth the views of their respective schools; in scholae there is a teacher and someone to be taught; the latter rarely speaks, never argues, maintains no view, and merely serves to give the other a reason for setting forth his own views.
